ent \"files go as the first argument\", but apparently the signature is\r\n\r\n```python\r\n    def __call__(message=None, files=None,  ...\r\n```\r\n\r\nso first one is the 'message' and that 'sub' was taken as the message while ignoring kward `message`. So it feels that there is absent some check somewhere to behave similar to python whenever there is a duplicate definition for a kwarg first through positional and then by the name\r\n\r\n```\r\n$> cat /tmp/2.py\r\ndef f(x=1, y=None):\r\n  print(x)\r\nf(1, x=2)\r\n\r\n$> python /tmp/2.py \r\nTraceback (most recent call last):\r\n  File \"/tmp/2.py\", line 3, in <module>\r\n    f(1, x=2)\r\nTypeError: f() got multiple values for keyword argument 'x'\r\n```", "closed_by": null, "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/datalad/datalad/issues/1542/reactions", "total_count": 0, "+1": 0, "-1": 0, "laugh": 0, "hooray": 0, "confused": 0, "heart": 0, "rocket": 0, "eyes": 0}, "timeline_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/datalad/datalad/issues/1542/timeline", "performed_via_github_app": null}